<paragraph id="8BF336EEFF830D2993829A60FD54FCA2" blockId="12.[178,1084,802,854]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253">
R e c o g n i t i o n 
<taxonomicName id="4C4C4D6DFF830D2992A59A61FDC8FCCF" baseAuthorityName="MOCSARY" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[405,620,802,824]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caucasica">
<emphasis id="B938EAFCFF830D2992A59A61FDC8FCCF" box="[405,620,802,824]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253">Podalonia caucasica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a glabrous propodeal enclosure, a small tooth on the claws near the base and a basally red gaster.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3566565FF830D2993829A25FD63FB8A" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF336EEFF830D2993829A25FD39FC24" blockId="12.[178,1085,869,979]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253">
Most females differ from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4C4D6DFF830D2992FA9A25FD8EFC8C" baseAuthorityName="W. KIRBY" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[458,554,869,891]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="B938EAFCFF830D2992FA9A25FD8EFC8C" box="[458,554,869,891]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253">P. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a smooth, shiny and sparsely punctate scutum (punctures 2-3 diameters apart), but it is variable and not all specimens can clearly be separated from that species. The female of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4C4D6DFF830D2991C09AE2FCCBFC41" box="[752,879,928,950]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gobiensis">
<emphasis id="B938EAFCFF830D2991C09AE2FCCBFC41" box="[752,879,928,950]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253">P. gobiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also similar and differs only by the criteria mentioned in the key.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF336EEFF830D2993829AA1FE54FBE2" blockId="12.[178,1084,994,1045]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253">
The male of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4C4D6DFF830D2992099AA0FE19FC0F" baseAuthorityName="MOCSARY" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[313,445,995,1016]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caucasica">
<emphasis id="B938EAFCFF830D2992099AA0FE19FC0F" box="[313,445,995,1016]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253">P. caucasica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C4C4D6DFF830D2991799AA0FD03FC0F" baseAuthorityName="W. KIRBY" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[585,679,994,1016]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Podalonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="B938EAFCFF830D2991799AA0FD03FC0F" box="[585,679,994,1016]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253">P. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and differs only by the shape of penis valve (figs 24, 44, 69 and 105).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF336EEFF830D2993829D66FE6EFBAF" blockId="12.[178,1084,1061,1112]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1253">
